<h2 id="on-page-seo-checks">On-Page SEO Checks</h2>
<p>On-page SEO covers the elements on each individual page that influence how search engines understand and rank your content. These checks should be applied to every important page on your site, starting with your highest-traffic and highest-value pages.</p>

<p><strong>1. Title tags are unique and descriptive.</strong> Every indexable page must have a unique title tag that includes the primary keyword, accurately describes the page content, and stays within 50-60 characters to avoid truncation in search results. Check for duplicate titles across the site — a common issue on large sites where template-generated pages share the same title pattern.</p>

<p><strong>2. Meta descriptions are compelling and unique.</strong> Each page should have a unique meta description of 120-155 characters that includes the primary keyword naturally, communicates a clear benefit or value proposition, and includes a subtle call to action. While meta descriptions are not a direct ranking factor, they significantly influence click-through rates from search results.</p>

<p><strong>3. H1 tag is present and singular.</strong> Every page should have exactly one H1 tag that contains the primary keyword and clearly communicates the page topic. The H1 should be the first heading on the page and should differ from the title tag to avoid redundancy while reinforcing the same topical signal.</p>

<p><strong>4. Heading hierarchy is logical.</strong> Headings should follow a sequential structure: H1 followed by H2s for major sections, H3s for subsections within H2s, and so on. Check for skipped heading levels (H1 jumping directly to H3), multiple H1 tags, and headings used purely for visual styling rather than structural organisation.</p>

<p><strong>5. Primary keyword appears in the first 100 words.</strong> Search engines give additional weight to keywords that appear early in the content. Verify that the primary keyword appears naturally within the opening paragraph of each target page.</p>

<p><strong>6. Images have descriptive alt text.</strong> Every informational image should have alt text that describes the image content and, where natural, includes relevant keywords. Decorative images should have empty alt attributes (alt="") to indicate they are not informational. Check for missing alt text across the entire site.</p>

<p><strong>7. URLs are clean and descriptive.</strong> Page URLs should be short, lowercase, use hyphens between words, include the primary keyword where natural, and avoid unnecessary parameters, session IDs, or category numbers. Check for URLs with excessive depth (more than three directory levels) or dynamic parameters that create duplicate content.</p>

<p><strong>8. Internal links use descriptive anchor text.</strong> Internal links should use anchor text that describes the linked page, not generic text like "click here" or "read more." Check that important pages receive sufficient internal links from relevant content pages, and that anchor text variation is natural rather than repetitively exact-match.</p>

<p><strong>9. External links point to authoritative sources.</strong> Outbound links to high-quality, relevant sources signal topical expertise and provide value to readers. Check that external links open in new tabs where appropriate, that linked sources are still live and relevant, and that sponsored or affiliate links carry appropriate rel attributes.</p>

<p><strong>10. Open Graph and Twitter Card tags are present.</strong> Social meta tags ensure your pages display correctly when shared on social platforms. Check that og:title, og:description, og:image, and twitter:card tags are present on all important pages with appropriate, compelling content.</p>

<h2 id="technical-seo-checks">Technical SEO Checks</h2>
<p>Technical SEO ensures search engines can effectively crawl, render, index, and rank your pages. Technical issues often have the highest impact on rankings because they can prevent entire sections of your site from being discovered or properly evaluated.</p>

<p><strong>11. Robots.txt is correctly configured.</strong> Your robots.txt file should allow access to all content you want indexed, block access to admin pages and private sections, reference your XML sitemap, and not accidentally block CSS or JavaScript files that search engines need to render your pages.</p>

<p><strong>12. XML sitemap is present and accurate.</strong> Your sitemap should list every indexable page, exclude non-indexable pages (noindexed, redirected, or error pages), be submitted to Google Search Console and Bing Webmaster Tools, and update automatically when pages are added or removed. Check that sitemap URLs match canonical URLs exactly.</p>

<p><strong>13. Canonical tags are correctly implemented.</strong> Every indexable page should have a self-referencing canonical tag. Pages with duplicate or near-duplicate content (such as paginated pages, filtered views, or HTTP/HTTPS variants) should canonicalise to the preferred version. Check for conflicting signals where the canonical tag points to a different URL than the one in the sitemap.</p>

<p><strong>14. HTTPS is fully implemented.</strong> All pages should load over HTTPS with no mixed content warnings. HTTP URLs should 301 redirect to HTTPS equivalents. Check that your SSL certificate is valid, not expired, and covers all subdomains in use.</p>

<p><strong>15. Page speed meets Core Web Vitals thresholds.</strong> Test your most important pages against Google's thresholds: LCP under 2.5 seconds, INP under 200 milliseconds, and CLS under 0.1. Use both lab data (Lighthouse) and field data (CrUX report in Search Console) to identify pages that fail. Common fixes include image compression, JavaScript deferral, font loading optimisation, and server-side caching.</p>

<p><strong>16. Mobile usability passes.</strong> All pages should be fully responsive and pass Google's mobile-friendly test. Check for common issues: text too small to read, touch targets too close together, content wider than the viewport, and viewport meta tag missing or misconfigured.</p>

<p><strong>17. No broken internal links (404 errors).</strong> Crawl your site and identify all internal links that return 404 status codes. Fix each by updating the link to the correct URL or implementing a 301 redirect from the broken URL to the most relevant live page.</p>

<p><strong>18. Redirect chains are resolved.</strong> Identify any URLs that redirect through multiple hops before reaching the final destination. Each hop may lose a small percentage of link equity and adds latency. Update redirects to point directly from the original URL to the final destination.</p>

<p><strong>19. Structured data is valid.</strong> Test your schema markup using Google's Rich Results Test. Check for required properties, correct data types, and alignment between structured data and visible page content. Invalid or misleading structured data can result in rich result eligibility loss or manual actions.</p>

<p><strong>20. Hreflang tags are correct (multilingual sites).</strong> If your site serves content in multiple languages or regions, verify that hreflang tags are present on all relevant pages, use correct language and region codes, include reciprocal references between all language versions, and specify an x-default fallback.</p>

<p><strong>21. Server response codes are correct.</strong> Crawl your site and check that live pages return 200, removed pages return 410 (or 301 to a relevant page), and no soft 404s exist (pages that display error content but return a 200 status code). Check server response time — TTFB should be under 600 milliseconds for most pages.</p>

<p><strong>22. JavaScript rendering works for search engines.</strong> If your site relies on client-side JavaScript to render content, verify that Google can see the fully rendered content using the URL Inspection tool in Search Console. Compare the rendered HTML to the initial HTML to identify content that depends on JavaScript execution.</p>

<h2 id="content-quality-checks">Content Quality Checks</h2>
<p>Content quality is increasingly central to Google's ranking decisions. These checks evaluate whether your content meets the standards required to rank and retain positions in competitive search results.</p>

<p><strong>23. No thin content pages are indexed.</strong> Identify pages with fewer than 300 words of unique content that are currently indexed. These pages should be expanded with substantive content, consolidated into more comprehensive pages, or noindexed if they serve a utility purpose but have no search value.</p>

<p><strong>24. No duplicate content exists.</strong> Check for pages with substantially identical content, including printer-friendly versions, HTTP and HTTPS duplicates, www and non-www duplicates, and parameterised URL variations. Resolve with canonical tags, 301 redirects, or content differentiation.</p>

<p><strong>25. Content matches search intent.</strong> For each target keyword, verify that your page format matches what Google is ranking. If the top results are all comparison guides and your page is a product page, you have an intent mismatch. Check the SERPs for your top 20 keywords and note any format misalignments.</p>

<p><strong>26. Content is comprehensive for its topic.</strong> Compare your content depth against top-ranking competitors. Are there subtopics they cover that you do not? Are there questions users commonly ask (visible in People Also Ask) that your content does not address? Content comprehensiveness is a key quality signal.</p>

<p><strong>27. No keyword cannibalisation.</strong> Check whether multiple pages target the same primary keyword. Use Google Search Console's Performance report filtered by query to identify keywords where multiple URLs appear. Resolve by consolidating content, differentiating keyword targets, or using canonical tags.</p>

<p><strong>28. E-E-A-T signals are present.</strong> Verify that content has clear author attribution, author bios display relevant credentials and experience, sources are cited where factual claims are made, publication and update dates are displayed, and the site includes an about page, contact page, and privacy policy.</p>

<p><strong>29. Content is fresh and updated.</strong> Identify pages with outdated information — old statistics, discontinued products, expired offers, or references to past events as if they are current. Prioritise updates for high-traffic pages where outdated content could erode trust and rankings.</p>

<p><strong>30. No orphan pages exist.</strong> Identify indexed pages that receive no internal links from other pages on your site. These orphan pages are difficult for search engines to discover and signal low importance within your site hierarchy. Either add internal links to them from relevant content or deindex them if they lack value.</p>

<h2 id="off-page-seo-checks">Off-Page SEO Checks</h2>
<p>Off-page SEO covers factors outside your website that influence rankings, primarily your backlink profile and external brand signals. These checks evaluate your site's authority and reputation from the search engine's perspective.</p>

<p><strong>31. Backlink profile is healthy.</strong> Review your backlink profile for toxic or spammy links that could trigger algorithmic penalties. Check the ratio of follow to nofollow links, anchor text distribution, and referring domain diversity. A profile dominated by links from a single source or with heavily exact-match anchor text warrants investigation.</p>

<p><strong>32. No toxic backlinks remain unaddressed.</strong> Use Ahrefs, SEMrush, or Google Search Console to identify potentially harmful backlinks. Verify each flagged link manually before adding to a disavow file. Submit the disavow file to Google if toxic links represent a significant portion of your profile.</p>

<p><strong>33. Link velocity is natural.</strong> Check whether your link acquisition rate shows any unnatural patterns — sudden spikes of hundreds of links in a short period, or periods of rapid loss. Natural link profiles grow gradually with organic variation. Unusual patterns may indicate spam attacks or algorithmic issues.</p>

<p><strong>34. Referring domain quality is adequate.</strong> Compare your domain authority distribution against competitors. If competitors have significantly more links from high-authority domains (DA 50+), this represents a competitive gap that content marketing and digital PR can address over time.</p>

<p><strong>35. Unlinked brand mentions exist.</strong> Search for mentions of your brand name that do not include a hyperlink. These represent easy outreach opportunities — the site has already mentioned you, and requesting a link is a natural follow-up. Tools like Ahrefs Content Explorer can automate this discovery.</p>

<p><strong>36. Social profiles are linked and active.</strong> Verify that your website links to official social media profiles, social profiles link back to your website, and social sharing metadata is correctly configured on all content pages.</p>

<h2 id="local-seo-checks">Local SEO Checks</h2>
<p>If your business serves customers in a specific geographic area, local SEO checks are essential for visibility in map results and local search queries.</p>

<p><strong>37. Google Business Profile is claimed and optimised.</strong> Verify that your GBP listing is claimed, that all information (name, address, phone, hours, categories, description) is accurate and complete, that photos are current and high quality, and that you are responding to reviews.</p>

<p><strong>38. NAP consistency across directories.</strong> Your business name, address, and phone number should be identical across your website, Google Business Profile, Bing Places, and all directory listings. Inconsistent NAP information confuses search engines and can suppress local rankings.</p>

<p><strong>39. Local schema markup is present.</strong> Your website should include LocalBusiness schema (or the appropriate subtype) with your address, phone number, opening hours, geographic coordinates, and service area. Verify the schema is valid using Google's Rich Results Test.</p>

<p><strong>40. Location pages are optimised (multi-location businesses).</strong> Each location should have a unique page with location-specific content, embedded map, NAP details, unique description, and local schema markup. Avoid duplicate content across location pages — each should contain genuinely unique information about that specific location.</p>

<p><strong>41. Reviews are actively managed.</strong> Check your review count and average rating on Google, and compare against local competitors. A strategy for soliciting reviews from satisfied customers should be in place. All reviews — positive and negative — should receive thoughtful responses.</p>

<p><strong>42. Local content exists.</strong> Pages targeting location-specific keywords (e.g., "SEO services in Manchester") should contain genuinely local content: references to the area, local case studies, knowledge of local market conditions. Thin pages that differ only in the city name inserted into a template add no value and risk being treated as doorway pages.</p>

<h2 id="how-to-use-this-checklist">How to Use This Checklist</h2>
<p>This checklist is designed as a working document, not a one-time read. Here is how to get the most value from it.</p>
<p><strong>Start with the highest-impact items.</strong> Not all checklist items carry equal weight. Technical checks that affect crawling and indexing (items 11-14) should be addressed before on-page optimisation, because no amount of on-page work matters if search engines cannot access your pages. Core Web Vitals (item 15) and content quality (items 23-30) are the next priority tier, followed by off-page and local checks.</p>
<p><strong>Audit in batches.</strong> Rather than checking all 42 items across every page simultaneously, work through the checklist in focused sessions. Dedicate one session to technical checks (which are typically site-wide), another to on-page checks (which require page-by-page review), and another to content quality assessment. This prevents fatigue and ensures thorough evaluation.</p>
<p><strong>Document findings as you go.</strong> For each check, record the current status (pass, fail, partial), the specific pages or elements affected, and the fix required. Our <a href="/website-audit-checklist/template/">downloadable audit template</a> provides a structured format for this documentation with scoring columns and priority ratings.</p>
<p><strong>Prioritise fixes by effort and impact.</strong> After completing the checklist, sort your findings into three categories: quick wins (high impact, low effort), strategic priorities (high impact, high effort), and maintenance items (low impact, variable effort). Execute quick wins first for immediate gains, then plan strategic priorities as projects.</p>
<p><strong>Schedule regular reviews.</strong> Technical and on-page checks should be reviewed quarterly. Content quality and off-page checks benefit from monthly monitoring. Local SEO checks should be reviewed monthly if local search is a significant traffic source. Use this checklist as your recurring review framework rather than recreating a new process each time.</p>
